{"title_page": "William A. Fletcher", "text_new": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{For|the Chief Justice of the Michigan Supreme Court|William A. Fletcher (Michigan jurist)}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox judge\n| honorific-prefix          =\n| name                      = William A. Fletcher\n| honorific-suffix          =\n| image                     =\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   =\n| office                    = Judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]]\n| term_start                = October 9, 1998\n| term_end                  =\n| nominator                 =\n| appointer                 = [[List of federal judges appointed by Bill Clinton|Bill Clinton]]\n| predecessor               = [[William Albert Norris]]\n| successor                 =\n| pronunciation             =\n| birth_name                = William Alan Fletcher\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1945|06|06}}\n| birth_place               = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date                =\n| death_place               =\n| death_cause               =\n| resting_place             =\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| citizenship               =\n| nationality               =\n| party                     =\n| otherparty                =\n| height                    =\n| spouse                    =\n| partner                   =\n| relations                 =\n| children                  =\n| parents                   = \n| mother                    = [[Betty Binns Fletcher]]\n| father                    =\n| relatives                 =\n| residence                 =\n| education                 = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])<br>[[Merton College, Oxford]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])<br>[[Yale Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])\n| alma_mater                =\n| occupation                =\n| profession                =\n| known_for                 =\n| salary                    =\n| net_worth                 =\n| cabinet                   =\n| committees                =\n| portfolio                 =\n| religion                  =\n| awards                    =\n| signature                 =\n| signature_alt             =\n| website                   =\n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n| footnotes                 =\n}}\n'''William Alan Fletcher''' (born June 6, 1945) is a [[United States federal judge|United States Circuit Judge]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]].<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=The American Bench|author1=Finn, M.T.|author2=Irvine, D.R.|author3=Bliss, M.L.|author4=Pratton, G.L.|author5=Morgan, S.|date=2009|publisher=Forster-Long|issn=0160-2578|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UrxFAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Education and legal training==\nFletcher went to [[Roosevelt High School (Seattle)|Roosevelt High School]] in [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], graduating in 1964. Fletcher received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[Harvard University]] in 1968 and another from [[Merton College, Oxford|Merton College]], [[Oxford University]] in 1970 as a [[Rhodes Scholar]]. He earned his [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Yale Law School]] in 1975.<ref name=BerkeleyCV>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.berkeley.edu/php-programs/faculty/facultyProfile.php?facID=39|title=Faculty Profiles: William A. Fletcher|work=law.berkeley.edu|accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref> He then clerked for  Judge [[Stanley A. Weigel]] from 1975 to 1976. Fletcher then clerked for [[Associate Justice]] [[William J. Brennan, Jr.]] of the [[United States Supreme Court]] from 1976 to 1977.\n\nFletcher's mother, [[Betty Binns Fletcher]], was also a judge on the Ninth Circuit, although she held [[senior status]] from 1998 until her death in 2012.\n\nFletcher teaches Federal Courts at the [[University of California, Berkeley, School of Law]] (Boalt Hall).<ref name=BerkeleyCV />\n\n==Professional career==\nFletcher was a [[Lieutenant]] in the [[United States Navy]] from 1970 to 1972 and a Professor of Law at [[Boalt Hall School of Law]], UC Berkeley from 1977 to 1998. Fletcher was the author of the Ninth Circuit's decision in ''Demers v. Austin'' (January 2014). He also published a 100-page dissent on the decision to deny [[Kevin Cooper (prisoner)|Kevin Cooper]] an ''en banc'' hearing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2009/05/11/05-99004o.pdf |title=Court documents |date=May 11, 2009 |website=cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov |format=PDF |access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n==Federal judicial service==\nFletcher was nominated twice by former [[President of the United States|President]] [[Bill Clinton]], his Rhodes Scholar classmate at Oxford, for a seat on the Ninth Circuit vacated by [[William Albert Norris]] in April 1995, and on January 7, 1997.<ref name=\"Wilson 2003 29-47\">{{Cite journal |last1=Wilson|first1=Sarah|title=Appellate Judicial Appointments During the Clinton Presidency: an Inside Perspective|journal= The Journal of Appellate Practice and Process|year=2003|pages=29\u201347}}</ref> His first nomination was never voted on by the Senate, but his second nomination was confirmed in a 57\u201341 vote on October 8, 1998 and he received his commission on October 9.<ref name=\"Wilson 2003 29-47\"/>\n\n==Judicial philosophy==\n\nFletcher is seen as a pragmatist on the court. When Fletcher makes a decision, he looks at both the facts of the case and the legal reasoning behind his decision. Fletcher reported in an interview that \"Probably the most important thing, beyond the obvious need for legal education of judges, is the development of a culture of decision making.  By this I mean a judicial culture in which it is expected that judges will\u2014to the extent of their ability and to the extent human nature will permit\u2014state carefully, fully, and honestly the factual and legal bases for their decisions.  I make no claim that American judges always live up to that ideal.  We do not.  But we try.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://cgc.law.stanford.edu/clc-spotlight/clc-1-201806-interview-1-jordan-corrente-beck/|title=CGCP Interview: Judge William A. Fletcher|first=China Guiding Cases|last=Project|website=China Guiding Cases Project}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Fletcher delivered the 2013 Madison Lecture, \"Our Broken Death Penalty\". Fletcher was very critical of the death penalty, saying the title \"suggests that it might have been unbroken. I think it's always been broken.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.findlaw.com/ninth_circuit/2013/10/judge-fletcher-like-his-mother-gives-nyu-death-penalty-lecture.html|title=Judge Fletcher, Like His Mother, Gives NYU Death Penalty Lecture|website=Findlaw}}</ref> In November 2014, in another speech Fletcher mentioned \"The death penalty may not discourage criminals from committing murder and is very expensive.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.cornell.edu/stories/2014/11/us-death-penalty-broken-judge-says|title=U.S. death penalty is broken, judge says|website=Cornell Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n==Notable rulings==\nFletcher has made rulings on women's rights, abortion, gun control, and the conditions of detainees at the border.\n\nOn October 22, 2002, Fletcher dissented in ''[[Jespersen v. Harrah's Operating Co.]]'' when the Ninth Circuit en banc ruled that a casino can require female workers to wear makeup.\n\nOn May 11, 2009, Fletcher wrote a 101 page dissent when the 9th circuit permitted the execution of Kevin Cooper to go forward. Fletcher noted that Cooper may have been innocent and was denied a fair trial. Fletcher also reasoned that Cooper may have been treated unfairly due to his race. He was joined by Judges [[Harry Pregerson]], [[Stephen Reinhardt]], [[Richard Paez]], and [[Johnnie B. Rawlinson]]. 6 other judges also dissented in denial of rehearing and agreed or mostly agreed with Fletcher's reasoning: [[Alex Kozinski]], [[Sidney Runyan Thomas]], [[Susan P. Graber]], [[Raymond C. Fisher]], [[Marsha S. Berzon]], and [[Kim McLane Wardlaw]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2009/05/11/05-99004o.pdf |title=No. 05-99004 |website=United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit |date=May 11, 2009 |accessdate=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\nOn June 3, 2014, Fletcher blocked an Arizona abortion law that basically prohibited all medication abortions. Fletcher wrote: \"We hold that plaintiffs have shown a likelihood of success on their claim that the Arizona law imposes an undue burden on a woman's right to abortion.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca9/14-15624/14-15624-2014-06-03.html|title=Planned Parenthood Arizona v. Humble, No. 14-15624 (9th Cir. 2014)|website=Justia Law}}</ref>\n\nOn December 29, 2015, Fletcher blocked a death sentence in regards that it was in violation of [[Roper v. Simmons]], and argued that Roper v. Simmons applies retroactively. Fletcher was joined by [[Sidney Runyan Thomas]], [[Kim McLane Wardlaw]], [[Marsha S. Berzon]], [[Morgan Christen]], and [[Jacqueline Nguyen]], over a dissent by [[Carlos Bea]] who argued that Roper v. Simmons did not apply retroactively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2015/12/29/09-99018.pdf |title=No. 09-99018 |website=United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit |date=December 29, 2015 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Fletcher wrote the majority opinion in ''[[Peruta v. San Diego County]]'', ruling that the Second Amendment did not protect the right to carry a concealed weapon. The San Diego ban on concealed weapons was upheld by a vote of 7\u20134.\n\nOn May 10, 2019, in a reluctant concurrence in a case where the 9th circuit permitted Trump to make asylum seekers wait in Mexico for immigration proceedings in court, Fletcher said of the Trump administration \"I am hopeful that the regular argument panel that will ultimately hear the appeal, with the benefit of full briefing and regularly scheduled argument, will be able to see the Government's arguments for what they are -- baseless arguments in support of an illegal policy that will, if sustained, require bona fide asylum applicants to wait in Mexico for years while their applications are adjudicated.\"  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.findlaw.com/ninth_circuit/2019/05/trump-wins-round-in-immigrant-policy----asylum-seekers-must-go-home.html|title=Trump Wins Round in Immigrant Policy -- Asylum-Seekers Must Go Home|website=Findlaw}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Fletcher dissented when the Ninth Circuit upheld Trump's gag rule restricting abortion funding by a vote of 7\u20134.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liveaction.org/news/ninth-circuit-abortion-businesses-titlex-rule-defund/ |title=Abortion businesses 'devastated' as Title X rule to defund goes into effect |publisher=Liveaction.org |date=2019-07-16 |accessdate=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOn August 12, 2019, Fletcher ruled that an animal does not constitute an \"individual\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2019/08/12/18-16327.pdf |title=Court documents |date=August 12, 2019 |website=cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov |format=PDF |access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOn August 15, 2019, Fletcher was in a 3\u20130 majority that ruled that detained migrant children must get sleep, soap, and clean water. The ruling was written by fellow 9th circuit judge [[Marsha S. Berzon]].<ref>{{cite web|author=11:02 PM ET |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/08/15/751634918/appeals-court-rules-detained-migrant-children-should-get-soap-sleep-clean-water |title=9th Circuit Court Of Appeals Says Detained Minors Must Get Food, Soap and Water |publisher=NPR |date=2019-08-15 |accessdate=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nIn oral arguments on June 18, 2019, Fletcher was very critical of the Trump administration's argument for denying the detained minors basic necessities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/media/view_video.php?pk_vid=0000015907|title=Watch recording for Jenny Flores v. William Barr, No. 17-56297|website=www.ca9.uscourts.gov}}</ref><ref>26:43-28:44</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2019, Fletcher reversed the district court\u2019s order allowing the government to seize funds from a pre-trial detainee\u2019s trust account to be applied to an outstanding restitution payment, ruling that they could not.<ref>http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2019/08/28/16-30194.pdf</ref>\n\nOn November 19, 2019, Fletcher granted relief to Vega-Anguiano, on the grounds that his 1998 removal order lacked a valid legal basis and the reinstatement order was improper. [[Morgan Christen]] concurred, noting that Vega-Anguiano could not have known that he needed to bring these errors to the agency's attention. [[Consuelo Callahan]] would have denied relief.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2019/11/19/15-72999.pdf |title=No. 15-72999 |website=United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit |date=November 19, 2019 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nOn December 24, 2019, Fletcher concurred in a ruling against police immunity. However, he criticized the Supreme Court's 1995 case Johnson v. Jones, writing\n\"I hope that the Supreme Court will revisit the issue soon and will disavow Johnson entirely. But until that happens, I believe that we are, unfortunately, bound to follow what remains of Johnson.\" <ref>http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2019/12/24/18-15665.pdf</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2020, Fletcher wrote for the majority (in a 7-4 decision) that Arizona's policy of not counting ballots filed in the wrong precinct is unconstitutional under Section 2 of the Voting Rights Act of 1965. Fletcher also ruled that Arizona had not carried its burden of showing that racial discrimination was not a factor in the making of this policy. Fletcher used maps to show why voters of Native American and Hispanic descent were far more likely to file a ballot at the wrong precinct, whether intentional (for convenience) or not. Fletcher also explained the longtime history of racial discrimination in Arizona.<ref>http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2020/01/27/18-15845.pdf</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2020, Fletcher, who was joined by Paez, ruled that asylum seekers could not be forced to be wait in Mexico while their hearings proceeded, mentioning that court proceedings often take years. However, on March 4, Fletcher and Paez narrowed the ruling to California and Arizona, letting the Supreme Court decide the rest.<ref>https://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2020/02/28/19-15716.pdf</ref><ref>https://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2020/03/04/19-15716_order.pdf</ref> However, the Supreme Court reversed Fletcher's ruling on March 11, allowing Trump's \"Remain-in-Mexico\" policy to continue. <ref>https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/487054-supreme-court-allows-trump-to-enforce-remain-in-mexico-policy</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FJC Bio|nid=1390781}}\n*{{C-SPAN|William Fletcher}}\n\n{{USCourtsOfAppealsJudges}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fletcher, William A.}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Merton College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Judges of the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]]\n[[Category:Law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:United States court of appeals judges appointed by Bill Clinton]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:UC Berkeley School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n", "text_old": "{{Short description|American judge}}\n{{For|the Chief Justice of the Michigan Supreme Court|William A. Fletcher (Michigan jurist)}}\n{{use mdy dates|date=December 2019}}\n{{Infobox judge\n| honorific-prefix          =\n| name                      = William A. Fletcher\n| honorific-suffix          =\n| image                     =\n| alt                       =\n| caption                   =\n| office                    = Judge of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]]\n| term_start                = October 9, 1998\n| term_end                  =\n| nominator                 =\n| appointer                 = [[List of federal judges appointed by Bill Clinton|Bill Clinton]]\n| predecessor               = [[William Albert Norris]]\n| successor                 =\n| pronunciation             =\n| birth_name                = William Alan Fletcher\n| birth_date                = {{Birth date and age|1945|06|06}}\n| birth_place               = [[Philadelphia]], [[Pennsylvania]]\n| death_date                =\n| death_place               =\n| death_cause               =\n| resting_place             =\n| resting_place_coordinates =\n| citizenship               =\n| nationality               =\n| party                     =\n| otherparty                =\n| height                    =\n| spouse                    =\n| partner                   =\n| relations                 =\n| children                  =\n| parents                   = \n| mother                    = [[Betty Binns Fletcher]]\n| father                    =\n| relatives                 =\n| residence                 =\n| education                 = [[Harvard University]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])<br>[[Merton College, Oxford]] ([[Bachelor of Arts|B.A.]])<br>[[Yale Law School]] ([[Juris Doctor|J.D.]])\n| alma_mater                =\n| occupation                =\n| profession                =\n| known_for                 =\n| salary                    =\n| net_worth                 =\n| cabinet                   =\n| committees                =\n| portfolio                 =\n| religion                  =\n| awards                    =\n| signature                 =\n| signature_alt             =\n| website                   =\n<!--Embedded templates / Footnotes-->\n| footnotes                 =\n}}\n'''William Alan Fletcher''' (born June 6, 1945) is a [[United States federal judge|United States Circuit Judge]] of the [[United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]].<ref name=\"google\">{{cite book|title=The American Bench|author1=Finn, M.T.|author2=Irvine, D.R.|author3=Bliss, M.L.|author4=Pratton, G.L.|author5=Morgan, S.|date=2009|publisher=Forster-Long|issn=0160-2578|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=UrxFAQAAIAAJ|accessdate=April 12, 2015}}</ref>\n\n==Education and legal training==\nFletcher went to [[Roosevelt High School (Seattle)|Roosevelt High School]] in [[Seattle, Washington|Seattle]], [[Washington (state)|Washington]], graduating in 1964. Fletcher received a [[Bachelor of Arts]] degree from [[Harvard University]] in 1968 and another from [[Merton College, Oxford|Merton College]], [[Oxford University]] in 1970 as a [[Rhodes Scholar]]. He earned his [[Juris Doctor]] from [[Yale Law School]] in 1975.<ref name=BerkeleyCV>{{cite web|url=http://www.law.berkeley.edu/php-programs/faculty/facultyProfile.php?facID=39|title=Faculty Profiles: William A. Fletcher|work=law.berkeley.edu|accessdate=March 31, 2011}}</ref> He then clerked for  Judge [[Stanley A. Weigel]] from 1975 to 1976. Fletcher then clerked for [[Associate Justice]] [[William J. Brennan, Jr.]] of the [[United States Supreme Court]] from 1976 to 1977.\n\nFletcher's mother, [[Betty Binns Fletcher]], was also a judge on the Ninth Circuit, although she held [[senior status]] from 1998 until her death in 2012.\n\nFletcher teaches Federal Courts at the [[University of California, Berkeley, School of Law]] (Boalt Hall).<ref name=BerkeleyCV />\n\n==Professional career==\nFletcher was a [[Lieutenant]] in the [[United States Navy]] from 1970 to 1972 and a Professor of Law at [[Boalt Hall School of Law]], UC Berkeley from 1977 to 1998. Fletcher was the author of the Ninth Circuit's decision in ''Demers v. Austin'' (January 2014). He also published a 100-page dissent on the decision to deny [[Kevin Cooper (prisoner)|Kevin Cooper]] an ''en banc'' hearing.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2009/05/11/05-99004o.pdf |title=Court documents |date=May 11, 2009 |website=cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov |format=PDF |access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\n==Federal judicial service==\nFletcher was nominated twice by former [[President of the United States|President]] [[Bill Clinton]], his Rhodes Scholar classmate at Oxford, for a seat on the Ninth Circuit vacated by [[William Albert Norris]] in April 1995, and on January 7, 1997.<ref name=\"Wilson 2003 29-47\">{{Cite journal |last1=Wilson|first1=Sarah|title=Appelate Judicial Appointments During the Clinton Presidency: an Inside Perspective|journal= The Journal of Appellate Practice and Process|year=2003|pages=29\u201347}}</ref> His first nomination was never voted on by the Senate, but his second nomination was confirmed in a 57\u201341 vote on October 8, 1998 and he received his commission on October 9.<ref name=\"Wilson 2003 29-47\"/>\n\n==Judicial philosophy==\n\nFletcher is seen as a pragmatist on the court. When Fletcher makes a decision, he looks at both the facts of the case and the legal reasoning behind his decision. Fletcher reported in an interview that \"Probably the most important thing, beyond the obvious need for legal education of judges, is the development of a culture of decision making.  By this I mean a judicial culture in which it is expected that judges will\u2014to the extent of their ability and to the extent human nature will permit\u2014state carefully, fully, and honestly the factual and legal bases for their decisions.  I make no claim that American judges always live up to that ideal.  We do not.  But we try.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://cgc.law.stanford.edu/clc-spotlight/clc-1-201806-interview-1-jordan-corrente-beck/|title=CGCP Interview: Judge William A. Fletcher|first=China Guiding Cases|last=Project|website=China Guiding Cases Project}}</ref>\n\nIn October 2013, Fletcher delivered the 2013 Madison Lecture, \"Our Broken Death Penalty\". Fletcher was very critical of the death penalty, saying the title \"suggests that it might have been unbroken. I think it's always been broken.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.findlaw.com/ninth_circuit/2013/10/judge-fletcher-like-his-mother-gives-nyu-death-penalty-lecture.html|title=Judge Fletcher, Like His Mother, Gives NYU Death Penalty Lecture|website=Findlaw}}</ref> In November 2014, in another speech Fletcher mentioned \"The death penalty may not discourage criminals from committing murder and is very expensive.\"<ref>{{cite web|url=https://news.cornell.edu/stories/2014/11/us-death-penalty-broken-judge-says|title=U.S. death penalty is broken, judge says|website=Cornell Chronicle}}</ref>\n\n==Notable rulings==\nFletcher has made rulings on women's rights, abortion, gun control, and the conditions of detainees at the border.\n\nOn October 22, 2002, Fletcher dissented in ''[[Jespersen v. Harrah's Operating Co.]]'' when the Ninth Circuit en banc ruled that a casino can require female workers to wear makeup.\n\nOn May 11, 2009, Fletcher wrote a 101 page dissent when the 9th circuit permitted the execution of Kevin Cooper to go forward. Fletcher noted that Cooper may have been innocent and was denied a fair trial. Fletcher also reasoned that Cooper may have been treated unfairly due to his race. He was joined by Judges [[Harry Pregerson]], [[Stephen Reinhardt]], [[Richard Paez]], and [[Johnnie B. Rawlinson]]. 6 other judges also dissented in denial of rehearing and agreed or mostly agreed with Fletcher's reasoning: [[Alex Kozinski]], [[Sidney Runyan Thomas]], [[Susan P. Graber]], [[Raymond C. Fisher]], [[Marsha S. Berzon]], and [[Kim McLane Wardlaw]]<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2009/05/11/05-99004o.pdf |title=No. 05-99004 |website=United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit |date=May 11, 2009 |accessdate=2019-12-11}}</ref>\n\nOn June 3, 2014, Fletcher blocked an Arizona abortion law that basically prohibited all medication abortions. Fletcher wrote: \"We hold that plaintiffs have shown a likelihood of success on their claim that the Arizona law imposes an undue burden on a woman's right to abortion.\" <ref>{{cite web|url=https://law.justia.com/cases/federal/appellate-courts/ca9/14-15624/14-15624-2014-06-03.html|title=Planned Parenthood Arizona v. Humble, No. 14-15624 (9th Cir. 2014)|website=Justia Law}}</ref>\n\nOn December 29, 2015, Fletcher blocked a death sentence in regards that it was in violation of [[Roper v. Simmons]], and argued that Roper v. Simmons applies retroactively. Fletcher was joined by [[Sidney Runyan Thomas]], [[Kim McLane Wardlaw]], [[Marsha S. Berzon]], [[Morgan Christen]], and [[Jacqueline Nguyen]], over a dissent by [[Carlos Bea]] who argued that Roper v. Simmons did not apply retroactively.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2015/12/29/09-99018.pdf |title=No. 09-99018 |website=United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit |date=December 29, 2015 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nIn 2016, Fletcher wrote the majority opinion in ''[[Peruta v. San Diego County]]'', ruling that the Second Amendment did not protect the right to carry a concealed weapon. The San Diego ban on concealed weapons was upheld by a vote of 7\u20134.\n\nOn May 10, 2019, in a reluctant concurrence in a case where the 9th circuit permitted Trump to make asylum seekers wait in Mexico for immigration proceedings in court, Fletcher said of the Trump administration \"I am hopeful that the regular argument panel that will ultimately hear the appeal, with the benefit of full briefing and regularly scheduled argument, will be able to see the Government's arguments for what they are -- baseless arguments in support of an illegal policy that will, if sustained, require bona fide asylum applicants to wait in Mexico for years while their applications are adjudicated.\"  <ref>{{cite web|url=https://blogs.findlaw.com/ninth_circuit/2019/05/trump-wins-round-in-immigrant-policy----asylum-seekers-must-go-home.html|title=Trump Wins Round in Immigrant Policy -- Asylum-Seekers Must Go Home|website=Findlaw}}</ref>\n\nIn July 2019, Fletcher dissented when the Ninth Circuit upheld Trump's gag rule restricting abortion funding by a vote of 7\u20134.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.liveaction.org/news/ninth-circuit-abortion-businesses-titlex-rule-defund/ |title=Abortion businesses 'devastated' as Title X rule to defund goes into effect |publisher=Liveaction.org |date=2019-07-16 |accessdate=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOn August 12, 2019, Fletcher ruled that an animal does not constitute an \"individual\".<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2019/08/12/18-16327.pdf |title=Court documents |date=August 12, 2019 |website=cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov |format=PDF |access-date=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nOn August 15, 2019, Fletcher was in a 3\u20130 majority that ruled that detained migrant children must get sleep, soap, and clean water. The ruling was written by fellow 9th circuit judge [[Marsha S. Berzon]].<ref>{{cite web|author=11:02 PM ET |url=https://www.npr.org/2019/08/15/751634918/appeals-court-rules-detained-migrant-children-should-get-soap-sleep-clean-water |title=9th Circuit Court Of Appeals Says Detained Minors Must Get Food, Soap and Water |publisher=NPR |date=2019-08-15 |accessdate=2019-10-02}}</ref>\n\nIn oral arguments on June 18, 2019, Fletcher was very critical of the Trump administration's argument for denying the detained minors basic necessities.<ref>{{cite web|url=https://www.ca9.uscourts.gov/media/view_video.php?pk_vid=0000015907|title=Watch recording for Jenny Flores v. William Barr, No. 17-56297|website=www.ca9.uscourts.gov}}</ref><ref>26:43-28:44</ref>\n\nOn August 28, 2019, Fletcher reversed the district court\u2019s order allowing the government to seize funds from a pre-trial detainee\u2019s trust account to be applied to an outstanding restitution payment, ruling that they could not.<ref>http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2019/08/28/16-30194.pdf</ref>\n\nOn November 19, 2019, Fletcher granted relief to Vega-Anguiano, on the grounds that his 1998 removal order lacked a valid legal basis and the reinstatement order was improper. [[Morgan Christen]] concurred, noting that Vega-Anguiano could not have known that he needed to bring these errors to the agency's attention. [[Consuelo Callahan]] would have denied relief.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2019/11/19/15-72999.pdf |title=No. 15-72999 |website=United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit |date=November 19, 2019 |accessdate=}}</ref>\n\nOn December 24, 2019, Fletcher concurred in a ruling against police immunity. However, he criticized the Supreme Court's 1995 case Johnson v. Jones, writing\n\"I hope that the Supreme Court will revisit the issue soon and will disavow Johnson entirely. But until that happens, I believe that we are, unfortunately, bound to follow what remains of Johnson.\" <ref>http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2019/12/24/18-15665.pdf</ref>\n\nOn January 27, 2020, Fletcher wrote for the majority (in a 7-4 decision) that Arizona's policy of not counting ballots filed in the wrong precinct is unconstitutional under Section 2 of the Voting Rights Act of 1965. Fletcher also ruled that Arizona had not carried its burden of showing that racial discrimination was not a factor in the making of this policy. Fletcher used maps to show why voters of Native American and Hispanic descent were far more likely to file a ballot at the wrong precinct, whether intentional (for convenience) or not. Fletcher also explained the longtime history of racial discrimination in Arizona.<ref>http://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2020/01/27/18-15845.pdf</ref>\n\nOn February 28, 2020, Fletcher, who was joined by Paez, ruled that asylum seekers could not be forced to be wait in Mexico while their hearings proceeded, mentioning that court proceedings often take years. However, on March 4, Fletcher and Paez narrowed the ruling to California and Arizona, letting the Supreme Court decide the rest.<ref>https://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2020/02/28/19-15716.pdf</ref><ref>https://cdn.ca9.uscourts.gov/datastore/opinions/2020/03/04/19-15716_order.pdf</ref> However, the Supreme Court reversed Fletcher's ruling on March 11, allowing Trump's \"Remain-in-Mexico\" policy to continue. <ref>https://thehill.com/regulation/court-battles/487054-supreme-court-allows-trump-to-enforce-remain-in-mexico-policy</ref>\n\n==See also==\n*[[List of law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n*{{FJC Bio|nid=1390781}}\n*{{C-SPAN|William Fletcher}}\n\n{{USCourtsOfAppealsJudges}}\n{{Portal bar|Biography}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Fletcher, William A.}}\n[[Category:1945 births]]\n[[Category:Alumni of Merton College, Oxford]]\n[[Category:American Rhodes Scholars]]\n[[Category:Harvard University alumni]]\n[[Category:Judges of the United States Court of Appeals for the Ninth Circuit]]\n[[Category:Law clerks of the Supreme Court of the United States]]\n[[Category:Living people]]\n[[Category:Lawyers from Philadelphia]]\n[[Category:United States court of appeals judges appointed by Bill Clinton]]\n[[Category:United States Navy officers]]\n[[Category:UC Berkeley School of Law faculty]]\n[[Category:Yale Law School alumni]]\n[[Category:20th-century American judges]]\n", "name_user": "Will Sandberg", "label": "safe", "comment": "", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/William_A._Fletcher"}
{"title_page": "CBS Sports", "text_new": "{{Infobox programming block\n| name = CBS Sports\n| image = CBS Sports logo.svg\n| premiered = {{Start date and age|1955}}\n| division = [[CBS]]\n| headquarters = [[New York City]]\n| major_contracts = ''[[NFL on CBS]]''<br />''[[College Basketball on CBS]]''<br />''[[NCAA March Madness (TV program)|NCAA March Madness]]''<br />''[[SEC on CBS]]''<br />''[[Masters Tournament]]''<br />''[[PGA Championship]]''<br />''[[PGA Tour on CBS]]''<br/>''[[Professional Bull Riders]]''\n| slogan = Then, Now and Always\n| key_people = [[Sean McManus (television executive)|Sean McManus]] {{small|(Chairman)}}<br />[[Joseph Ianniello]] {{small|(Chairman and CEO, CBS Entertainment Group)}}\n| parent = [[ViacomCBS]]\n| sister = [[CBS Sports Network]]<br />[[CBS Sports HQ]]\n| website = {{url|www.cbssports.com}}\n}}\n\n'''CBS Sports''' is the sports division of the American television network [[CBS]]. Its headquarters are in the [[CBS Building]] on West 52nd Street in [[midtown Manhattan]], New York City, with programs produced out of Studio 43 at the [[CBS Broadcast Center]] on West [[57th Street (Manhattan)|57th Street]].\n\nIts premier sports properties are professional basketball (including [[BIG3]] and the [[WNBA]]), [[NFL on CBS|NFL]], [[SEC on CBS|Southeastern Conference (SEC) football]], [[National Collegiate Athletics Association|NCAA]] basketball (including telecasts of the [[NCAA March Madness (TV program)|NCAA Men's Basketball Tournament]]), and [[PGA Tour]] golf, including [[Masters Tournament|The Masters]] and the [[PGA Championship]].\n\nThe online arm of CBS Sports is [[CBSSports.com]]. CBS purchased SportsLine.com in 2004, and today CBSSports.com is part of [[CBS Interactive]]. On February 26, 2018, following up on the success of their online news network [[CBSN]], CBS Sports launched [[CBS Sports HQ]], a 24/7, online only, linear sports news network. The network focuses entirely on sports news, results, highlights and analysis.<ref>{{cite web|title=What is CBS SPORTS HQ? Your guide to our new 24/7 streaming sports news network|url=https://www.cbssports.com/general/news/what-is-cbs-sports-hq-your-guide-to-new-247-streaming-sports-news-network/|website=CBSSports.com|date=February 26, 2018|accessdate=August 7, 2018}}</ref> (CBS Sports college sports and golf programming that it distributes over the air is generally made available for free via separate streams, as are a limited number of NFL national telecasts; the remainder requires a [[CBS All Access]] subscription to be viewed online, with [[CBS Sports Network]] programming requiring a [[TV Everywhere]] subscription.)\n\nCBS Sports was honored at the 59th Annual [[Technology & Engineering Emmy Award]]s for Outstanding Achievement in Advanced Media Technology for Synchronous Enhancement of Original Television Content for Interactive Use for its program ''[[NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Championship|March Madness]] on Demand.''\n\nOn August 31, 2013, CBS Sports rolled out its previous graphics and animation package that was first used in the network's coverage of [[Super Bowl XLVII]]. Additionally, in compliance with the [[Active Format Description]] #10 code, CBS Sports switched to a [[16:9 aspect ratio]] letterbox presentation used for all sports programming, including the ''SEC on CBS'' and the ''NFL on CBS'' broadcasts.\n\nOn November 30, 2015, CBS Sports released a new logo in order to coincide with the network's coverage of [[Super Bowl 50]]. The network also created a new on-air graphics package that debuted as part of the network's Super Bowl week programming. Following the game, the graphics package began to be utilized across all of their programming events, including their joint production of ''[[NCAA March Madness (CBS/Turner)|NCAA March Madness]]'' with [[Turner Sports]].<ref name=\"NewCBSSportsLogo2015\">{{cite web|author=Eye on Football staff|title=CBS Sports to debut new logo for Super Bowl 50|url=http://www.cbssports.com/nfl/eye-on-football/25395009/cbs-sports-to-debut-new-logo-for-super-bowl-50|publisher=CBS Sports|date=November 30, 2015|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite press release|title=CBS SPORTS ANNOUNCES NEW LOGO|url=http://cbspressexpress.com/cbs-sports/releases/view?id=44042|publisher=CBS Press Express|date=November 30, 2015|accessdate=November 30, 2015}}</ref> [[Masters Tournament|The Masters]], which retains heavy production control over their event, continued to use the network's older graphical style originally unveiled in 2007 until 2019, when they debuted a new graphics package. Also, the network's ''Thursday Night Football'' game broadcasts continued to use the graphical style originally used since its debut in 2014 until its rights to that package expired in 2018.\n\n==Programs throughout the years==\n===Current programs===\n* ''[[PGA Tour on CBS]]'' ('''1956\u2013present''')\n** [[Masters Tournament|The Masters]] ([[1956 Masters Tournament|1956]]\u2013present)\n** [[PGA Championship]] ([[1991 PGA Championship|1991]]\u2013present)\n* ''[[CBS Sports Spectacular]]'' ('''1960\u2013present''')\n* College football (1950s\u20131966, '''1968\u2013present''')\n** [[Sun Bowl]] ([[1968 Sun Bowl|1968]]\u2013present)\n** ''[[SEC on CBS]]'' (First pick of [[Southeastern Conference|SEC]] games, 1996\u20132023)\n** [[Army\u2013Navy Game]] (1962\u20131963, 1982, 1984\u20131990, [[1996 NCAA Division I-A football season|1996]]\u2013present)\n* [[College Basketball on CBS|''Road to the Final Four'']] ('''1981\u2013present''')\n** [[NCAA March Madness (CBS/Turner)|NCAA Tournament]] ([[1982 NCAA Division I Men's Basketball Tournament|1982]]\u2013present)\n* ''[[NFL on CBS]]'' ([[1956 NFL season|1956]]\u2013[[1993 NFL season|1993]], '''[[1998 NFL season|1998]]\u2013present''')\n** ''[[The NFL Today]]'' ([[1975 NFL season|1975]]\u2013[[1993 NFL season|1993]], [[1998 NFL season|1998]]\u2013present)\n** [[Super Bowl]]: [[Super Bowl I|I]] (shared with [[NBC]]), [[Super Bowl II|II]], [[Super Bowl IV|IV]], [[Super Bowl VI|VI]], [[Super Bowl VIII|VIII]], [[Super Bowl X|X]], [[Super Bowl XII|XII]], [[Super Bowl XIV|XIV]], [[Super Bowl XVI|XVI]], [[Super Bowl XVIII|XVIII]], [[Super Bowl XXI|XXI]], [[Super Bowl XXIV|XXIV]], [[Super Bowl XXVI|XXVI]], [[Super Bowl XXXV|XXXV]], [[Super Bowl XXXVIII|XXXVIII]], [[Super Bowl XLI|XLI]],<br /> [[Super Bowl XLIV|XLIV]], [[Super Bowl XLVII|XLVII]], [[Super Bowl 50|50]], [[Super Bowl LIII|LIII]] and [[Super Bowl LV|LV]]\n* [[Professional Bull Riders]] ('''2013\u2013present''')\n* [[BIG3]] ('''2019\u2013present''')\n* [[NBA on CBS|WNBA on CBS Sports Network]] ('''2019\u2013present''')\n*''[[Tennis on CBS]]''\n**[[World TeamTennis]] ('''2019\u2013present''')\n**[[Davis Cup]] ('''2020\u2013present''') (USA matches only for qualifiers)<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.daviscup.com/en/news/316033.aspx|title=Davis Cup - Where to watch the Davis Cup Qualifiers|last=|first=|date=|website=[[Davis Cup]]|url-status=live|archive-url=|archive-date=|access-date=2020-03-06}}</ref>\n* [[NWSL]] (2020-present)\n\n===Former programs===\n* ''[[Major League Baseball on CBS]]'' ([[1947 Major League Baseball season|1947]]\u2013[[1950 Major League Baseball season|1950]], [[1955 Major League Baseball season|1955]]\u2013[[1965 Major League Baseball season|1965]], [[1990 Major League Baseball season|1990]]\u2013[[1993 Major League Baseball season|1993]])\n** [[World Series]]: {{wsy|1947}} (Games 3 and 4), {{wsy|1948}}\u2013{{wsy|1950}}, {{wsy|1990}}\u2013{{wsy|1993}}\n* ''[[Thoroughbred Racing on CBS]]''\n** [[Kentucky Derby]] (1952\u20131974)\n** [[Preakness Stakes]] (1960\u20131976)\n** [[Belmont Stakes]] (1960\u20131985)\n* [[Little League World Series]] (1953)\n* ''[[SEC on CBS|College Football on CBS]]''\n** [[Orange Bowl]] ([[1953 Orange Bowl|1953]]\u2013[[1961 Orange Bowl|1961]]; [[1996 Orange Bowl (January)|1996]]\u2013[[1998 Orange Bowl|1998]])\n** [[Gator Bowl]] ([[1956 Gator Bowl|1956]]\u2013[[1963 Gator Bowl|1963]], [[198