]]\n* ''[[Thursday Night Football]]'' \u2013 [[James Brown (sportscaster)|James Brown]], [[Rich Eisen]]\n\n====Behind the scenes====\n* [[Don Robertson (television announcer)|Don Robertson]]\n\n==Presidents of CBS Sports==\n* [[Robert Wussler]] (1976\u20131978)\n* [[Frank M. Smith, Jr.]] (1978\u20131980)\n* [[Van Gordon Sauter]] (1980\u20131981)<ref>{{cite news|last=Associated Press|title=Sauter Will Head CBS News|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=November 10, 1981}}</ref>\n* [[Neal Pilson]] (1981\u20131984)<ref name=Pilson>{{cite news|last=Craig|first=Jack|title=Pilson is leaving CBS Sports|url=|newspaper=Boston Globe|date=March 19, 1994}}</ref>\n* Peter Lund (1984<ref>{{cite news|title=CBS Not Happy With Losing Philly|newspaper=Philadelphia Daily News|date=December 12, 1984}}</ref>\u20131986)<ref>{{cite news|last=Harasta|first=Cathy|title=CBS Plans to Announce Corporate Restructuring|newspaper=The Dallas Morning News|date=December 15, 1986}}</ref>\n* [[Neal Pilson]] (1986\u20131994)<ref name=\"Pilson\" />\n* David Kenin (1994<ref>{{cite news|title=Rebuilding CBS Sports|newspaper=Miami Herald|date=June 10, 1994}}</ref>\u20131996)<ref name=\"McManus\">{{cite news|title=CBS Sports president Kenin loses job|newspaper=Journal Sentinel|date=November 6, 1996}}</ref>\n* [[Sean McManus (television executive)|Sean McManus]] (1996\u20132013)<ref name=\"McManus\" />\n* David Berson (2013\u2013present)\n\n==CBS Sports Network==\n{{Main|CBS Sports Network}}\n[[File:CBS Sports Network 2016.png|right|150px]]\n'''CBS Sports Network''' is a sports-oriented American [[digital cable]] and [[satellite television|satellite]] channel that is operated by [[ViacomCBS]] through CBS Sports. Launched as the National College Sports Network in 2002, then renamed as College Sports Television in 2003, CBS's then-parent company [[Viacom (original)|Viacom]] acquired the network in 2005 and later renamed it '''CBS College Sports Network''' in 2008. The network had always focused on college sports, but in 2011, CBS rebranded the network as '''CBS Sports Network''' as a move to reposition the network to include mainstream sports\u2014including coverage of minor professional sports leagues such as the [[Arena Football League]] and [[Major League Lacrosse]], although college sports are still aired frequently by the network.\n\n==CBS Sports Radio==\n{{Main|CBS Sports Radio}}\n[[File:CBS Sports Radio Logo.png|150px|right]]\n'''CBS Sports Radio''' is a [[sports radio]] network that launched on September 4, 2012 with hourly sports news updates. It began offering a full 24-hour schedule of sports talk programming on January 2, 2013.<ref name=pressrelease>[http://www.cbspressexpress.com/cbs-radio/releases/view?id=32154 CBS creates the largest major market sports radio network in the nation] CBS Radio official press release, June 21, 2012</ref> CBS Sports Radio although originally owned by [[CBS Radio]] is now owned directly by [[CBS Corporation]] and operated by [[Entercom]], with [[Westwood One]] handling distribution and marketing of the network. Sports radio stations that are owned by Entercom and [[Cumulus Media]] carry part of the full schedule of programming, while eight Entercom-owned stations carry network programming throughout the day. In addition to carriage on terrestrial stations, CBS Sports Radio also streams its programming on the internet.<ref name=pressrelease/>\n\n==CBS Sports HQ==\n{{Main|CBS Sports HQ}}\n[[File:CBS Sports HQ.png|150px|right]]\nOn February 26, 2018, CBS Sports launched CBS Sports HQ, a 24-hour streaming sports news channel modeled after [[CBS News]]'s streaming news channel [[CBSN]].<ref>{{Cite news|url=http://deadline.com/2018/02/cbs-launches-cbs-sports-hq-24-hour-streaming-network-1202301326/|title=CBS Launches Free 24-Hour Sports Streaming Network CBS Sports HQ|last=Chmielewski|first=Dawn C.|date=2018-02-26|work=Deadline|access-date=2018-03-05|language=en-US}}</ref>\n\n==Main competitors==\n* [[ESPN]]\n** [[ESPN2]]\n** [[ESPNews]]\n** [[ESPNU]]\n** [[ESPN on ABC]]\n* [[Fox Sports (United States)|Fox Sports]]\n** [[Fox Sports 1|FS1]]\n** [[Fox Sports 2|FS2]]\n* [[NBC Sports]]\n** [[NBCSN]]\n* [[Turner Sports]]\n** [[AT&T SportsNet]]\n* [[Univision|Univisi\u00f3n]]\n** [[Univision Deportes Network|Univisi\u00f3n Deportes]]\n\n==See also==\n\n* [[CBSSports.com]]\n* [[CBS Sports Network]]\n* [[CBS Sports Radio]]\n* [[CBS Corporation]]\n\n==References==\n{{Reflist}}\n\n==External links==\n* {{Official website}}\n\n{{Navboxes\n|list =\n{{CBS Sports}}\n{{Sports television in the United States}}\n{{The NFL Today CBS}}\n{{Presidents of CBS Sports}}\n{{Webby Awards|cat=Sports|type=winner|year=1998}}\n}}\n\n[[Category:1955 establishments in New York (state)]]\n[[Category:CBS Sports| ]]\n[[Category:Webby Award winners]]\n", "name_user": "Rodw", "label": "safe", "comment": "Disambiguating links toCharles Davis(link changed toCharles Davis (defensive back)) usingDisamAssist.", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/CBS_Sports"}
{"title_page": "Eve Watkinson", "text_new": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Irish stage, film and television actress.}}\n{{Infobox person\n| name        = Eve Watkinson\n| image       =Eve_Watkinson.jpg\n\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = 6 March 1909\n| birth_place = [[Terenure]]\n| death_date  = 15 November 1999\n| death_place = [[Monkstown, County Dublin]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  =Actress\n| title       =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| nationality = Irish\n}}\n'''Eve Watkinson''' (6 March 1909 \u2013 15 November 1999) was an Irish stage, film and television actress.\n\n==Biography==\nEve Panton Watkinson was born 6 March 1909 in [[Terenure]] to Arthur Panton Watkinson and Kate n\u00e9e Hollingsworth.<ref name=\"Census\">{{cite web |title=house 1 in Healthfield Road (Terenure, Dublin) |url=http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Dublin/Terenure/Healthfield_Road/42038/ |website=National Archives: Census of Ireland 1911 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Birth record\">{{cite web |title=Birth record search |url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/images/birth_returns/births_1909/01614/1647294.pdf |website=Irish genealogy - Civil Records |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Her father was the director of an interior decorating company called A. Panton Watkinson on St Stephen's Green. She learned acting working with an amateur group in [[Capel Street]] called [[Torch Theatre, Dublin|Torch Theatre]]. She went on to work with [[Edward Pakenham, 6th Earl of Longford|Edward]] and [[Christine Longford]]'s company based in the [[Gate Theatre]]. Watkinson performed in leading roles in plays by Ibsen, Sheridan, Coleman, Shakespeare and Fry. She played the Vampire Monster Mallarka in ''[[Carmilla]]'' and gained that became her nickname with the company. Left an inheritance enough to live on, Watkinson used the money she earned in acting to produce productions of her own.<ref name=\"The Irish Times 2020\">{{cite web | title=Monster Mallarka of Dublin theatre | website=The Irish Times | date=7 April 2020 | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/monster-mallarka-of-dublin-theatre-1.254881 | access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWatkinson also spent several years with the [[Bristol Old Vic]] Theatre company.<ref name=\"Wearing 2014 p. 442\">{{cite book | last=Wearing | first=J.P. | title=The London Stage 1950-1959: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel | publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers | series=The London Stage | year=2014 | isbn=978-0-8108-9308-5 | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=5g2PBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA442 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=442}}</ref> When [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] began to produce television plays, she had several roles including in plays by D\u00fcrrenmatt, [[Christopher Nolan (author)|Christopher Nolan]] and Frank O'Connor. She went with Torchlight and Laser Beams to the Edinburgh Festival. She also worked as a presenter for RTE Radio.<ref name=\"Radio\">{{cite web |title=RT\u00c9 Radio Scripts |url=https://www.ucd.ie/archives/t4media/p0260-rte-radio-talk%20-scripts-in-english-descriptive-catalogue.pdf |publisher=UCD |page=12 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> In the 1960s Watkinson narrated stories for children.<ref name=\"Billboard p. 23\">{{cite magazine | title=Special Merit Albums |work=Billboard | publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc. | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=ARgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT23 | date=24 November 1962 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=23}}</ref>  Watkinson had a role in the 1988 Irish film ''[[Reefer and the Model]]''. Watkinson died in [[Monkstown, County Dublin|Monkstown]] 15 November 1999.<ref name=\"The Irish Times 2020\"/><ref name=\"Dobson 2010 p. 308\">{{cite book | last=Dobson | first=N. | title=The A to Z of Animation and Cartoons | publisher=Scarecrow Press | series=A to Z guides | year=2010 | isbn=978-0-8108-7623-1 | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=dJRa_8AJkkUC&pg=PA308 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=308}}</ref>\n\n==Excerpt Playography==\n* ''Hedda Gabler''\n* ''Rosmersholm''\n* ''The Lady from the Sea''\n* ''The Dark is Light Enough''\n* ''The School for Scandal''\n* ''The Jealous Wife''\n* ''The Physicists''\n* ''The Moment next to nothing''\n* ''Torchlight and Laser Beams''\n* ''The Moses Rock''\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watkinson, Eve}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish television actresses]]\n", "text_old": "{{Use dmy dates|date=April 2020}}\n{{short description|Irish stage, film and television actress.}}\n{{Infobox Person\n| name        = Eve Watkinson\n| image       =Eve_Watkinson.jpg\n\n| image_size  =\n| caption     =\n| birth_name  =\n| birth_date  = 6 March 1909\n| birth_place = [[Terenure]]\n| death_date  = 15 November 1999\n| death_place = [[Monkstown, County Dublin]]\n| death_cause =\n| residence   =\n| other_names =\n| known_for   =\n| education   =\n| employer    =\n| occupation  =Actress\n| title       =\n| salary      =\n| networth    =\n| parents     =\n| relatives   =\n| nationality = Irish\n}}\n'''Eve Watkinson''' (6 March 1909 \u2013 15 November 1999) was an Irish stage, film and television actress.\n==Biography==\nEve Panton Watkinson was born 6 March 1909 in [[Terenure]] to Arthur Panton Watkinson and Kate n\u00e9e Hollingsworth.<ref name=\"Census\">{{cite web |title=house 1 in Healthfield Road (Terenure, Dublin) |url=http://www.census.nationalarchives.ie/pages/1911/Dublin/Terenure/Healthfield_Road/42038/ |website=National Archives: Census of Ireland 1911 |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref><ref name=\"Birth record\">{{cite web |title=Birth record search |url=https://civilrecords.irishgenealogy.ie/churchrecords/images/birth_returns/births_1909/01614/1647294.pdf |website=Irish genealogy - Civil Records |access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> Her father was the director of an interior decorating company called A. Panton Watkinson on St Stephen's Green. She learned acting working with an amateur group in [[Capel Street]] called [[Torch Theatre, Dublin|Torch Theatre]]. She went on to work with [[Edward Pakenham, 6th Earl of Longford|Edward]] and [[Christine Longford]]'s company based in the [[Gate Theatre]]. Watkinson performed in leading roles in plays by Ibsen, Sheridan, Coleman, Shakespeare and Fry. She played the Vampire Monster Mallarka in ''[[Carmilla]]'' and gained that became her nickname with the company. Left an inheritance enough to live on, Watkinson used the money she earned in acting to produce productions of her own.<ref name=\"The Irish Times 2020\">{{cite web | title=Monster Mallarka of Dublin theatre | website=The Irish Times | date=7 April 2020 | url=https://www.irishtimes.com/news/monster-mallarka-of-dublin-theatre-1.254881 | access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref>\n\nWatkinson also spent several years with the [[Bristol Old Vic]] Theatre company.<ref name=\"Wearing 2014 p. 442\">{{cite book | last=Wearing | first=J.P. | title=The London Stage 1950-1959: A Calendar of Productions, Performers, and Personnel | publisher=Rowman & Littlefield Publishers | series=The London Stage | year=2014 | isbn=978-0-8108-9308-5 | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=5g2PBAAAQBAJ&pg=PA442 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=442}}</ref> When [[Raidi\u00f3 Teilif\u00eds \u00c9ireann]] began to produce television plays, she had several roles including in plays by Durrenmatt, [[Christopher Nolan (author)|Christopher Nolan]] and Frank O'Connor. She went with Torchlight and Laser Beams to the Edinburgh Festival. She also worked as a presenter for RTE Radio. <ref name=\"Radio\">{{cite web |title=RT\u00c9 Radio Scripts |url=https://www.ucd.ie/archives/t4media/p0260-rte-radio-talk%20-scripts-in-english-descriptive-catalogue.pdf |publisher=UCD |page=12 ||access-date=10 April 2020}}</ref> In the 1960s Watkinson narrated stories for children.<ref name=\"Billboard p. 23\">{{cite magazine | title=Special Merit Albums |work=Billboard | publisher=Nielsen Business Media, Inc. | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=ARgEAAAAMBAJ&pg=PT23 | date=24 November 1962 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=23}}</ref>  Watkinson had a role in the 1988 Irish film ''[[Reefer and the Model]]''. Watkinson died in [[Monkstown, County Dublin|Monkstown]] 15 November 1999.<ref name=\"The Irish Times 2020\"/><ref name=\"Dobson 2010 p. 308\">{{cite book | last=Dobson | first=N. | title=The A to Z of Animation and Cartoons | publisher=Scarecrow Press | series=A to Z guides | year=2010 | isbn=978-0-8108-7623-1 | url=https://books.google.ie/books?id=dJRa_8AJkkUC&pg=PA308 | access-date=10 April 2020 | page=308}}</ref>\n\n==Excerpt Playography==\n* ''Hedda Gabler''\n* ''Rosmersholm''\n* ''The Lady from the Sea''\n* ''The Dark is Light Enough''\n* ''The School for Scandal''\n* ''The Jealous Wife''\n* ''The Physicists''\n* ''The Moment next to nothing''\n* ''Torchlight and Laser Beams''\n* ''The Moses Rock''\n\n==References==\n\n{{Reflist}}\n\n{{Authority control}}\n\n{{DEFAULTSORT:Watkinson, Eve}}\n[[Category:1909 births]]\n[[Category:1999 deaths]]\n[[Category:People from Dublin]]\n[[Category:20th-century Irish actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish stage actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish film actresses]]\n[[Category:Irish television actresses]]\n", "name_user": "CAPTAIN RAJU", "label": "safe", "comment": "clean up,typo(s) fixed: Durrenmatt \u2192 D\u00fcrrenmatt", "url_page": "//en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Eve_Watkinson"}
